# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eleanora-knopf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:eleanora-knopf/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The **American Museum of Natural History** (**AMNH**) is a natural history museum on the Upper West Side of Manhattan in New York City.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Located in Theodore Roosevelt Park, across the street from Central Park, the museum complex comprises 21 interconnected buildings housing 45 permanent exhibition halls, in addition to a planetarium and a library.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] AMNH has a full-time scientific staff of 225, sponsors over 120 special field expeditions each year, and averages about five million visits annually.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The AMNH is a private 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Bickmore devised the idea for the American Museum of Natural History in 1861, and, after several years of advocacy, the museum opened within Central Park's Arsenal on May 22, 1871.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's first purpose-built structure in Theodore Roosevelt Park was designed by Calvert Vaux and J.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Wrey Mould and opened on December 22, 1877.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Numerous wings have been added over the years, including the main entrance pavilion (named for Theodore Roosevelt) in 1936 and the Rose Center for Earth and Space in 2000.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Bickmore devised the idea for the American Museum of Natural History in 1861.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At the time, he was studying in Cambridge, Massachusetts, at Louis Agassiz's Museum of Comparative Zoology.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Upon the end of the American Civil War, Bickmore asked numerous prominent New Yorkers, such as William E.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Although Dodge himself could not fund the museum at the time, he introduced the naturalist to Theodore Roosevelt Sr., the father of future U.S. president Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Calls for a natural history museum increased after Barnum's American Museum burned down in 1868.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Eighteen prominent New Yorkers wrote a letter to the Central Park Commission that December, requesting the creation of a natural history museum in Central Park.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Central Park commissioner Andrew Haswell Green indicated his support for the project in January 1869.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A board of trustees was created for the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The next month, Bickmore and Joseph Hodges Choate drafted a charter for the museum, which the board of trustees approved without any changes.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It was in this charter that the "American Museum of Natural History" name was first used.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Bickmore said he wanted the museum's name to reflect his "expectation that our museum will ultimately become the leading institution of its kind in our country", similar to the British Museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Before the museum was established, Bickmore needed to secure approval from Boss Tweed, leader of the powerful and corrupt Tammany Hall political organization.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The legislation to establish the American Museum of Natural History had to be signed by John Thompson Hoffman, the governor of New York, who was associated with Tweed.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Hoffman signed the legislation creating the museum on April 6, 1869, with John David Wolfe as its first president.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Subsequently, the chairman of the AMNH's executive committee asked Green if the museum could use the top two stories of Central Park's Arsenal, and Green approved the request in January 1870.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Insect specimens were placed on the lower level of the Arsenal, while stones, fossils, mammals, birds, fish, and reptiles were placed on the upper level.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum opened within the Arsenal on May 22, 1871.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The AMNH became popular in the following years.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Arsenal location had 856,773 visitors in the first nine months of 1876 alone, more than the British Museum had recorded for all of 1874.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Meanwhile, the AMNH's directors had identified Manhattan Square (bounded by Eighth Avenue/Central Park West, 81st Street, Ninth Avenue/Columbus Avenue, and 77th Street) as a site for a permanent structure.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Several prominent New Yorkers had raised $500,000 to fund the construction of the new building.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The city's park commissioners then reserved Manhattan Square as the site of the permanent museum, and another $200,000 was raised for the building fund.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Numerous dignitaries and officials, including U.S. president Ulysses S.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Grant, attended the museum's groundbreaking ceremony on June 3, 1874.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum opened on December 22, 1877, with a ceremony attended by U.S. president Rutherford B.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The old exhibits were removed from the Arsenal in 1878, and the AMNH was debt-free by the next year.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Originally, the AMNH was accessed by a temporary bridge that crossed a ditch, and it was closed during Sundays.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's trustees voted in May 1881 to complete the approaches from Central Park, and work began later that year.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The landscape changes were nearly complete by mid-1882, and a bridge over Central Park West opened that November.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At this point, the AMNH's Manhattan Square building and the Arsenal could not physically fit any more objects, and the existing facilities, such as the 100-seat lecture hall, were insufficient to accommodate demand.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The trustees began discussing the possibility of opening the museum on Sundays in May 1885, and the state legislature approved a bill permitting Sunday operations the next year.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Despite advocacy from the working class, the trustees opposed Sunday operations because it would be expensive to do so.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At the time, the museum was open to the general public on Wednesdays through Saturdays, and it was open exclusively to members on Mondays and Tuesdays.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's collections continued to grow during the 1880s, and it hosted various lectures through the 19th century.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] With several departments having been crowded out of the original building, New York state legislators introduced bills to expand the AMNH in early 1887; thousands of teachers endorsed the legislation.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Kellogg was directed to prepare plans for landscaping the site.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In March 1888, the trustees approved an entrance pavilion at the center of the 77th Street elevation.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The New York City Board of Estimate began soliciting bids from general contractors in late 1889.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Many of the objects and specimens in the museum's collection could not be displayed until the annex was opened.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original building was refurbished during 1890, and the museum's library was transferred to the west wing that year.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The AMNH's trustees considered opening the museum on Sundays by February 1892 and stopped charging admission that July.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum began Sunday operations in August, and the southern entrance pavilion opened that November.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Even with the new wing, there was still not enough space for the museum's collection.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The city's Park Board approved a new lecture hall in January 1893, but the hall was postponed that May in favor of a wing extending east on 77th Street.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A contract to furnish the east wing was awarded in June 1894.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] When the east wing was nearly completed in February 1895, the AMNH's trustees asked state legislators for $200,000 to build a wing extending west on 77th Street.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The east wing was still being furnished by August; its ground floor opened that December.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's funds and collections continued to grow during this time.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A hall of mammals opened within the museum in November 1896.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] That year, the AMNH received approval to extend the east wing northward along Central Park West, creating an L-shaped structure.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Plans for an expanded east wing were approved in June 1897, and a contract was awarded two months later.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Jesup also sponsored worldwide expeditions to obtain objects for the collection.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] By mid-1898, the west wing, the expanded east wing, and a lecture hall at the center of the museum were underway; however, the project encountered delays due to a lack of city funding.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The west and east wings, with several exhibit halls, were nearly complete by late 1899, but the lecture hall had been delayed.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A hall dedicated to ancient Mexican art opened that December.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's 1,350-seat lecture hall opened in October 1900, as did the Native American and Mexican halls in the west wing.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] During the 1900s, the AMNH sponsored several expeditions to grow its collection, including a trip to Mexico, a trip to collect fauna from the Pacific Northwest, a trip to collect art in China, and an expedition to collect rocks in local caves.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] One such exhibition yielded a brontosaurus skeleton, which was the centerpiece of the dinosaur hall that opened in February 1905.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In the early 1920s, museum president Henry Fairfield Osborn planned a new entrance for the AMNH, which was to contain a memorial to Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Also around that time, the New York state government formed a commission to study the feasibility of a Roosevelt memorial.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] After a dispute over whether to put the memorial in Albany or in New York City, the government of New York City offered a site next to the AMNH for consideration.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The commission rejected a "conventional Greek mausoleum" design, instead opting to design a triumphal arch and hall in a Roman style.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 1925, the AMNH's trustees hosted an architectural design competition, selecting John Russell Pope to design the memorial hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Construction began in 1929, and the trustees approved final plans the next year.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Harry McNally was the general contractor.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Roosevelt's cousin, U.S. president Franklin D.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Roosevelt, dedicated the memorial on January 19, 1936.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original building was later known as "Wing A".
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] During the 1950s, the top floor was renovated into a library, being redecorated with what Christopher Gray of *The New York Times* described as "dropped ceilings and the other usual insults".
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The ten-story Childs Frick Building, which contained the AMNH's fossil collection, was added to the museum in the 1970s.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The architect Kevin Roche and his firm Roche-Dinkeloo have been responsible for the master planning of the museum since the 1990s.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Various renovations to both the interior and exterior have been carried out.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Renovations to the Dinosaur Hall were undertaken beginning in 1991, and Roche-Dinkeloo designed the eight-story AMNH Library in 1992.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's Rose Center for Earth and Space was completed in 2000.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 2001, the museum's lecture hall was renamed the Samuel J. and Ethel LeFrak Theater, after Samuel J.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] LeFrak donated US$8 million to the AMNH.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's south facade, spanning 77th Street from Central Park West to Columbus Avenue, was cleaned and repaired, re-emerging in 2009.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Steven Reichl, a spokesman for the museum, said that work would include restoring 650 black-cherry window frames and stone repairs.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum's consultant on the latest renovation was Wiss, Janney, Elstner Associates, Inc., an architectural and engineering firm with headquarters in Northbrook, Illinois.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum also restored the mural in Roosevelt Memorial Hall in 2010.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 2026, the AMNH received $2 million to help fund the renovation of the Pacific Birds Hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 2014, the museum published plans for a $325 million, 195,000 ft2 (18,100 m2) annex, the Richard Gilder Center for Science, Education, and Innovation, on the Columbus Avenue side.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It was named after stockbroker and philanthropist Richard Gilder.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] On October 11, 2016, the Landmarks Preservation Commission unanimously approved the expansion.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Construction of the Gilder Center, which was expected to break ground the next year following design development and Environmental Impact Statement stages, would entail demolition of three museum buildings built between 1874 and 1935.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum filed plans for the expansion in August 2017, but due to community opposition, construction did not start until June 2019.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] On May 4, 2023, the Gilder Center opened, and the museum had 1.5 million visitors over the next three months.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 2025, the AMNH began providing free "Discoverer" memberships to Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program recipients.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In late 2023, the museum announced that it would stop displaying human remains from its collection.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Despite the 1990 passage of the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act (NAGPRA), as late as 2023, the AMNH held an estimated 1,900 Native American remains that had not been repatriated.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In January 2024, the museum closed a number of displays and the AMNH's Eastern Woodlands and Great Plains halls, or about 10,000 square feet.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum agreed to repatriate the remains that July.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original Victorian Gothic building was designed by Calvert Vaux and J.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Wrey Mould, both already closely identified with the architecture of Central Park.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Vaux and Mould's original plan was intended to complement the Metropolitan Museum of Art on the opposite side of Central Park.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original building, as constructed, was at the center of the 77th Street frontage and measured 199 by 66 feet (61 by 20 m) across; it featured a gallery measuring 112 feet (34 m) long200 ft (61 m) tall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] This gallery contained a raised basement, three stories of exhibits, Venetian Gothic arches, and an attic with dormers and a slate roof.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The rear of the gallery included two towers: one containing a stairwell and the other containing curators' rooms.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original structure still exists but is hidden from view by the many buildings in the complex that today occupy most of Manhattan Square.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The museum remains accessible through its 77th Street foyer, which has since been renamed the Grand Gallery.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The full plan called for twelve pavilions similar in design to the original building.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Eight pavilions would have been arranged as the sides of a square, while the remaining four would be perpendicular to each other in the interior of the square.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There were to be eight towers along the perimeter of the square, as well as a 120 ft-wide (37 m) dome in the center, at the intersection of the four interior pavilions.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In each pavilion, there was to be a ground floor; the second floor was to contain a gallery; the third floor was to exhibit specimens; and the fourth floor was to be used for research.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Upon the intended completion of the master plan, the museum would measure 850 ft (260 m) from north to south and 650 ft (200 m) from west to east, including projections from the square.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The finished structure, with a ground area of over 18 acres (7.3 ha), would have been the largest building in North America, as well as the largest museum building in the world.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The master plan was never fully realized; by 2015, the museum consisted of 25 separate buildings that were poorly connected.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The original building was soon eclipsed by the west and east wings of the southern frontage, designed by J.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Cleaveland Cady as a brownstone neo-Romanesque structure.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It extends 700 ft (210 m) along West 77th Street, with corner towers 150 ft (46 m) tall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Its pink brownstone and granite, similar to that found at Grindstone Island in the St.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Lawrence River, came from quarries at Picton Island, New York.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The southern wing contains several halls ranging in size from 60 by 110 feet (18 m × 34 m) to 30 ft × 125 ft (9.1 m × 38.1 m).
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At the ends of either wings are rounded turret-like towers.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The main entrance hall on Central Park West is formally known as the **New York State Memorial to Theodore Roosevelt**.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Completed by John Russell Pope in 1936, it is an over-scaled Beaux-Arts monument to former U.S. president Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall was originally supposed to have formed one end of an "Intermuseum Promenade" through Central Park, connecting with the Metropolitan Museum of Art to the east, but the promenade was never completed.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The memorial hall has a pink-granite facade, which is modeled after Roman arches.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In front of the hall on Central Park West is a terrace measuring 350 ft (110 m) long, as well as a series of steps.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The main entrance consists of an arch measuring 60 ft (18 m) high.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The underside of the arch is a coffered granite vestibule, which leads to a bronze, glass, and marble screen.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It is flanked by two pairs of columns, which are topped by figures of American explorers John James Audubon, Daniel Boone, Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] These figures were sculpted by James Earle Fraser and are about 30 ft (9.1 m) high.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In the attic above the main archway, there is an inscription describing Roosevelt's accomplishments.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The words "Truth", "Knowledge", and "Vision" are carved into the entablature under this inscription.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Fraser also designed an equestrian statue of Theodore Roosevelt, flanked by a Native American and an African American, which originally stood outside the memorial hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In the 21st century, the statue generated controversy due to its subordinate depiction of these figures behind Roosevelt.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] This prompted AMNH officials to announce in 2020 that they would remove the statue.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The statue was removed in January 2022 and will be on a long-term loan to the Theodore Roosevelt Presidential Library in North Dakota.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The interior of the Memorial Hall measures 67 by 120 ft (20 by 37 m) across, with a barrel-vaulted ceiling measuring 100 ft (30 m) tall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The ceiling contains octagonal coffers, while the floors are made of mosaic marble tiles.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The lowest 9 ft (2.7 m) of the walls are wainscoted in marble, above which the walls of the memorial hall are made of limestone.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The top of each wall contains a marble band and a Corinthian entablature.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Each of the Memorial Hall's four sides contains two red-marble columns, each measuring 48 ft (15 m) tall and rising from a Botticino marble pedestal.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There are rounded windows at clerestory level on the north and south walls.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] William Andrew MacKay designed three 62 ft-wide (19 m) murals depicting important events in Roosevelt's life: the construction of the Panama Canal on the north wall, African exploration on the west wall, and the Treaty of Portsmouth on the south wall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The east and west walls, contain four quotes from Roosevelt under the headings "Nature", "Manhood", "Youth", and "The State".
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Memorial Hall originally connected to various classrooms, exhibition rooms, and a 600-person auditorium.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Directly underneath the Memorial Hall is an entrance to the 81st Street–Museum of Natural History station.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Today, the hall connects to the Akeley Hall of African Mammals and the Hall of Asian Mammals.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Memorial Hall contains four exhibits that describe Theodore Roosevelt's conservation activities in his youth, early adulthood, U.S. presidency, and post-presidency.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Named after taxidermist Carl Akeley, the Akeley Hall of African Mammals is a two-story hall on the second floor, directly west of the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It connects to the Hall of African Peoples to the west.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of African Mammals' 28 dioramas depict in meticulous detail the great range of ecosystems found in Africa and the mammals endemic to them.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The centerpiece of the hall is a herd of eight African elephants in a characteristic 'alarmed' formation.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Though the mammals are typically the main feature in the dioramas, birds and flora of the regions are occasionally featured as well.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall in its current form was completed in 1936.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of African Mammals was first proposed to the museum by Carl Akeley around 1909; he proposed 40 dioramas featuring the rapidly vanishing landscapes and animals of Africa.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Daniel Pomeroy, a trustee of the museum and partner at J.P.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Morgan & Co., offered investors the opportunity to accompany the museum's expeditions in Africa in exchange for funding.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Akeley began collecting specimens for the hall as early as 1909, famously encountering Theodore Roosevelt in the midst of the Smithsonian-Roosevelt African expedition.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] On these early expeditions, Akeley was accompanied by his former apprentice in taxidermy, James L.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] When Akeley returned to Africa to collect gorillas for the hall's first diorama, Clark remained behind and began scouring the country for artists to create the backgrounds.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The eventual appearance of the first habitat groups impacted the design of other diorama halls, including Birds of the World, the Hall of North American Mammals, the Vernay Hall of Southeast Asian Mammals, and the Hall of Oceanic Life.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] After Akeley's unexpected death during the Eastman-Pomeroy expedition in 1926, responsibility of the hall's completion fell to James L.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Clark, who hired architectural artist James Perry Wilson in 1933 to assist Leigh in the painting of backgrounds.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Wilson made many improvements on Leigh's techniques, including a range of methods to minimize the distortion caused by the dioramas' curved walls.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 1936, William Durant Campbell, a wealthy board member with a desire to see Africa, offered to fund several dioramas if allowed to obtain the specimens himself.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Clark agreed to this arrangement, resulting in the acquisition of numerous large specimens.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Kane joined Leigh, Wilson, and several other artists in completing the hall's remaining dioramas.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Though construction of the hall was completed in 1936, the dioramas gradually opened between the mid-1920s and early 1940s.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Asian Mammals, sometimes referred to as the Vernay-Faunthorpe Hall of Asian Mammals, is directly south of the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It contains 8 complete dioramas, 4 partial dioramas, and 6 habitat groups of mammals and locations from India, Nepal, Burma, and Malaysia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall opened in 1930 and, similar to the Akeley Hall of African Mammals, is centered around 2 Asian elephants.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At one point, a giant panda and Siberian tiger were also part of the Hall's collection, originally intended to be part of an adjoining Hall of North Asian Mammals (planned in the current location of Stout Hall of Asian Peoples).
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] These specimens can currently be seen in the Hall of Biodiversity.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Specimens for the Hall of Asian Mammals were collected over six expeditions led by British-born antiques dealer Arthur S.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] John Faunthorpe (as noted by stylized plaques at both entrances).
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The expeditions were funded entirely by Vernay, who characterized the expense as a British tribute to American involvement in World War I.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The first Vernay-Faunthorpe expedition took place in 1922, when many of the animals Vernay was seeking, such as the Sumatran rhinoceros and Asiatic lion, were facing the possibility of extinction.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Vernay made many appeals to regional authorities to obtain hunting permits; in later museum-related expeditions headed by Vernay, these appeals helped the museum gain access to areas previously restricted to foreign visitors.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Rosenkranz accompanied the Vernay-Faunthorpe expeditions as field artist and painted the majority of the diorama backgrounds in the hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] These expeditions were also well documented in both photo and video, with enough footage of the first expedition to create a feature-length film, *Hunting Tigers in India* (1929).
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Bernard Family Hall of North American Mammals is on the first floor, directly west of the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall. features 43 dioramas of various mammals of the American continent, north of tropical Mexico.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Each diorama places focus on a particular species, ranging from the largest megafauna to the smaller rodents and carnivorans.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Notable dioramas include the Alaskan brown bears looking at a salmon after they scared off an otter, a pair of wolves, a pair of Sonoran jaguars, and dueling bull Alaska moose.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of North American Mammals opened in 1942 with only ten dioramas.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] A massive restoration project began in late 2011 following a large donation from Jill and Lewis Bernard.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In October 2012 the hall was reopened as the Bernard Hall of North American Mammals.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Small Mammals is an offshoot of the Bernard Family Hall of North American Mammals, directly to the west of the latter.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There are several small dioramas featuring small mammals found throughout North America, including collared peccaries, Abert's squirrel, and a wolverine.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Sanford Hall of North American birds is a one-story hall on the third floor, between the Hall of Primates and Akeley Hall's second level.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There are over 20 dioramas depicting birds from across North America in their native habitats.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] At the far end of the hall is an old mural of pink flamingos by ornithologist and artist Louis Agassiz Fuertes.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall also has display cases devoted to large collections of warblers, owls, and raptors.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Conceived by museum ornithologist Frank Chapman, the Hall is named for Chapman's friend and amateur ornithologist Leonard C.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Sanford, who partially funded the hall and also donated the entirety of his own bird specimen collection to the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Construction began on the hall's dioramas as early as 1902, and the dioramas opened in 1909.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] They were the first to be exhibited in the museum and are the oldest still on display.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Although Chapman was not the first to create museum dioramas, he was the first to bring artists into the field with him in the hopes of capturing a specific location at a specific time.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In contrast to the dramatic scenes that Akeley created for the African Hall, Chapman wanted his dioramas to evoke a scientific realism, ultimately serving as a historical record of habitats and species facing a high probability of extinction.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Each of Chapman's dioramas depicted a species, their nests, and 4 ft (1.2 m) of the surrounding habitat in each direction.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Birds of the World is on the south side of the second floor.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The global diversity of bird species is exhibited in this hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] 12 dioramas showcase various ecosystems around the world and provide a sample of the varieties of birds that live there.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Example dioramas include South Georgia featuring king penguins and skuas, the East African plains featuring secretarybirds and bustards, and the Australian outback featuring honeyeaters, cockatoos, and kookaburras.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Whitney Memorial Wing, originally named after Harry Payne Whitney and comprising 750,000 birds, opened in 1939.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Later known as the Hall of Oceanic Birds, it was completed and dedicated in 1953.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It was founded by Frank Chapman and Leonard C.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Sanford, originally museum volunteers, who had gone forward with creation of a hall to feature birds of the Pacific islands.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall was designed as a completely immersive collection of dioramas, including a circular display featuring birds-of-paradise.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 1998, the Butterfly Conservatory was installed inside the hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Reptiles and Amphibians is near the southeast corner of the third floor.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It serves as an introduction to herpetology, with many exhibits detailing reptile evolution, anatomy, diversity, reproduction, and behavior.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Notable exhibits include a Komodo dragon group, an American alligator, Lonesome George, the last Pinta Island tortoise, and poison dart frogs.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Defosse, and Emmett Reid Dunn collected specimens of the Komodo Dragon for the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Burden's chapter "The Komodo Dragon", in *Look to the Wilderness*, describes the expedition, the habitat, and the behavior of the dragon.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall opened in 1927 and was rebuilt from 1969 to 1977 at a cost of $1.3 million.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of Biodiversity is underneath the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall primarily contains exhibits and objects highlighting the concept of biodiversity, the interactions between living organisms, and the negative impacts of extinction on biodiversity.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall includes a 2,500 ft2 (230 m2) diorama depicting the Dzanga-Sangha Special Reserve rainforest with over 160 animal and plant species.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The diorama shows the rainforest in three states: pristine, altered by human activity, and destroyed by human activity.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Another attraction in the hall is "The Spectrum of Habitats", a video wall displaying footage of nine ecosystems.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] There is a "Transformation Wall", containing information and stories detailing changes to biodiversity, and a "Solutions Wall", containing suggestions on how to increase biodiversity.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Hall of North American Forests is a one-story hall on the museum's first floor in between the Theodore Roosevelt Memorial Hall and the Warburg Hall of New York State Environments.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It contains ten dioramas depicting a range of forest types from across North America as well as several displays on forest conservation and tree health.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall was constructed under the guidance of botanist Henry K.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Each diorama specifically lists both the location and exact time of year depicted.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Trees and plants featured in the dioramas are constructed of a combination of art supplies and actual bark and other specimens collected in the field.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The entrance to the hall features a cross section from the Mark Twain Tree, 1,400-year-old sequoia taken from the King's River grove on the west flank of the Sierra Mountains in 1891.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Warburg Hall of New York State Environments is a one-story hall on the museum's ground floor in between the Hall of North American Forests and the Grand Hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Based on the town of Pine Plains in Dutchess County, New York, the hall gives a multi-faceted presentation of the eco-systems typical of New York.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Aspects covered include soil types, seasonal changes, and the impact of both humans and nonhuman animals on the environment.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It is named for the German-American philanthropist Felix M.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Warburg and opened on May 14, 1951, as the Warburg Memorial Hall of General Ecology.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It has changed little since and is now frequently regarded for its retro-modern styling.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The Milstein Hall of Ocean Life is in the southeastern quadrant of the first floor, west of the Hall of Biodiversity.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It focuses on marine biology, botany and marine conservation.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The center of the hall contains a 94 ft (29 m)-long blue whale model.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The upper level of the hall exhibits the vast array of ecosystems present in the ocean.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Dioramas compare and contrast the life in these different settings including kelp forests, mangroves, coral reefs, the bathypelagic, among others.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It attempts to show how vast and varied the oceans are while encouraging common themes throughout.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The lower half of the hall consists of 15 large dioramas of larger marine organisms.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] It is on this level that the famous "Squid and the Whale" diorama sits, depicting a hypothetical fight between the two creatures.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Other notable exhibits in this hall include the two-level Andros Coral Reef Diorama.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Osborn proposed the construction of a large building in the museum's southeast courtyard to house a new Hall of Ocean Life in which "models and skeletons of whales" would be exhibited.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall opened in 1924 and was renovated in 1962.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] In 1969, a renovation gave the hall a more explicit focus on oceanic megafauna, including the addition of a lifelike blue whale model to replace a popular steel and papier-mâché whale model that had hung in the Biology of Mammals hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] Richard Van Gelder oversaw the creation of the hall in its current incarnation.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The hall was renovated once again in 2003, this time with environmentalism and conservation being the main focal points, and was renamed after developer Paul Milstein and AMNH board member Irma Milstein.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p01] The 2003 renovation included refurbishment of the famous blue whale, suspended high above the 19,000 ft2 (1,800 m2) exhibit floor; updates to the 1930s and 1960s dioramas; and electronic displays.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Stout Hall of Asian Peoples is a one-story hall on the museum's second floor in between the Hall of Asian Mammals and Birds of the World.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Stout, a former president of the museum, and was primarily organized by Walter A.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Fairservis, a longtime museum archaeologist.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Opened in 1980, Stout Hall is the museum's largest anthropological hall and contains artifacts acquired by the museum between 1869 and the mid-1970s.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Many famous expeditions sponsored by the museum are associated with the artifacts in the hall, including the Roy Chapman Andrews expeditions in Central Asia and the Vernay-Hopwood Chindwin expedition.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Stout Hall has two sections: Ancient Eurasia, a small section devoted to the evolution of human civilization in Eurasia, and Traditional Asia, a much larger section containing cultural artifacts from across the Asian continent.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The latter section is organized to geographically correspond with two major trade routes of the Silk Road.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Like many of the museum's exhibition halls, the artifacts in Stout Hall are presented in a variety of ways including exhibits, miniature dioramas, and five full-scale dioramas.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Notable exhibits in the Ancient Eurasian section include reproductions from the archaeological sites of Teshik-Tash and Çatalhöyük, as well as a full size replica of a Hammurabi Stele.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Traditional Asia section contains areas devoted to major Asian countries, such as Japan, China, Tibet, and India, while also including a vast array of smaller Asian tribes including the Ainu, Semai, and Yakut.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of African Peoples is behind Akeley Hall of African Mammals and underneath Sanford Hall of North American Birds.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It is organized by the four major ecosystems found in Africa: River Valley, Grasslands, Forest-Woodland, and Desert.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Each section presents artifacts and exhibits of the peoples native to the ecosystems throughout Africa.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall contains three dioramas and notable exhibits include a large collection of spiritual costumes on display in the Forest-Woodland section.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Uniting the sections of the hall is a multi-faceted comparison of African societies based on hunting and gathering, cultivation, and animal domestication.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Each type of society is presented in a historical, political, spiritual, and ecological context.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A small section of African diaspora spread by the slave trade is also included.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Mexico and Central America is a one-story hall on the museum's second floor behind Birds of the World and before the Hall of South American Peoples.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It presents archaeological artifacts from a broad range of pre-Columbian civilizations that once existed across Mesoamerica, including the Maya, Olmec, Zapotec, and Aztec.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Because the great majority of the written records of these civilizations did not survive the Spanish conquest, the overarching aim of the hall is to piece together what it is possible to know about them from the artifacts alone.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum has displayed pre-Columbian artifacts since its opening, only a short time after the discovery of the civilizations by archaeologists, with its first hall dedicated to the subject opening in 1899.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As the museum's collection grew, the hall underwent major renovations in 1944 and again in 1970 when it re-opened in its current form.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Notable artifacts on display include the Kunz Axe and a full-scale replica of Tomb 104 from the Monte Albán archaeological site, originally displayed at the 1939 World's Fair.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of South American Peoples is a one-story hall on the northwestern corner of the second floor, next to the Hall of Mexico and Central America.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall was first opened on the third floor in 1904, and exhibited archaeological objects, including mummies, from Peru, Colombia, Bolivia, and the West Indies.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In 1931, the hall was expanded and relocated to the second floor under the direction of curators Ronald Olson and W.C.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The new hall included a recreation of a Chilean copper mine, and later, a temporary hall titled the Men of the Montaña, which featured Peruvian cultural artifacts from the Cashibo, and Panoan peoples.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In 1989, the Hall was renovated and reopened as a permanent exhibition, focusing on the technology and artistry of the ancient Andean and traditional Amazonian cultures, led by curators Craig Morris, Junius Bird, and Robert Carneiro.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall contains roughly 2,300 objects from various ancient South American cultures, including the Moche, Chávin, Chancay, Paracas, Nazca, and Inca.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A number of the artifacts on display come from the Roosevelt Collections, which were collected by Theodore Roosevelt on expeditions to South America in the early 20th century and donated to the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Pacific Peoples is on the southwestern corner of the third floor, accessed through the Hall of Plains Indians.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The cultural anthropologist Margaret Mead had founded the Hall of Pacific Peoples in 1971.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] From the time Mead began curatorial work on the hall in 1945, she conceived an exhibit environment that would emulate sights and sounds from the Pacific regions on display.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] After Mead's death in 1978, the hall reopened in December 1984 as the Margaret Mead Hall of Pacific Peoples.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The new hall, designed by Eugene Burgmann, maintained the blue-themed ocean and sky ambiance of the original hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall was once again closed in 1997 and reopened in 2001 with an updated design that retained the geocultural "alcoves" first installed with the 1984 remodel.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Margaret Mead Hall of Pacific Peoples contains artifacts from New Zealand, Australia, Indonesia, the Philippines, Micronesia, Melanesia and other Pacific islands.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Mead had collected 250 of the 1,500 items in the hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Some of these were probably selected from the 3,284 items she collected for the American Museum of Natural History during fieldwork in New Guinea and other Pacific island locations, 1928–1939.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Others, such as the theatrical set from a puppet play in Bali, were chosen from among the approximately 600 items that Mead and her anthropologist husband Gregory Bateson had sent to the American Museum of Natural History while they were conducting fieldwork in Bali, 1936–1938.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The exhibits in the Margaret Mead Hall of Pacific Peoples also include a fiberglass cast of an Easter Island *moai* statue and capes made of honeycreeper feathers.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Northwest Coast Hall is a one-story hall on the museum's ground floor behind the Grand Gallery and in between Warburg and Spitzer Halls. it is the museum's oldest hall, having been established in 1899 by anthropologist Franz Boas as the Jesup North Pacific Hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall now contains artifacts and exhibits of the tribes of the North Pacific Coast cultural region (Southern Alaska, Northern Washington, and a portion of British Columbia).
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Featured prominently in the hall are four "House Posts" from the Kwakwaka'wakw nation and murals by William S.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As of 2022, there are 9,000 items in total, including 78 totem poles, as well as a Haida canoe suspended from the ceiling (relocated from the Grand Gallery in 2020).
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The artifacts are accompanied by text in numerous Native American languages.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Artifacts in the hall originated from three main sources.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The earliest of these was a gift of Haida artifacts collected by John Wesley Powell and donated by future trustee Heber R.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] This was followed by the museum's purchase of two collections of Tlingit artifacts collected by Lt.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The remainder of the hall's artifacts were collected during the famed Jesup North Pacific Expedition between 1897 and 1902.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Led by Boas and financed by museum president Morris Ketchum Jesup, the expedition was the first for the museum's Division of Anthropology and is now considered the "foremost expedition in American anthropology".
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Many famous ethnologists took part, including George Hunt, who secured the Kwakwaka'wakw House Posts in the hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Other tribes featured in the hall include Coastal Salish, Nuu-chah-nulth, Tsimshian, and Nuxalk.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] At the time of its opening, the Northwest Coast Hall was one of four halls dedicated to the native peoples of United States and Canada.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It was originally organized in two sections, the first being a general area pertaining to all peoples of the region and the second a specialized area divided by tribe.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] This was a point of contention for Boas who wanted all artifacts in the hall to be associated with the proper tribe (much like it is currently organized), eventually leading to the dissolution of Boas's relationship with the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In May 2022, the hall reopened after a five-year, $19 million renovation, with more than 1,000 artifacts on view.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The new display includes work from contemporary artists such as Greg Colfax KlaWayHee and Robert Davidson.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Plains Indians is on the south side of the third floor, near the western end of the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The primary focus of this hall is the North American Great Plains peoples as they were at the middle of the 19th century, including depictions of Blackfeet (*see also: Blackfoot Confederacy*), Hidatsa, and Dakota cultures.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Of particular interest is a Folsom point discovered in 1926 New Mexico, providing evidence of early American colonization of the Americas.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Eastern Woodlands Indians is next to the Hall of Plains Indians, on the south side of the third floor.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It details the lives and technology of traditional Native American peoples in the woodland environments of eastern North America.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] These include Cree, Mohegan, Ojibwe, and Iroquois cultures.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The exhibit features examples of indigenous basketry, pottery, farming techniques, food preparation, metal jewelry, musical instruments, and textiles.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Other highlights include a model of a Menominee birchbark canoe and various traditional lodgings such as an Ojibwa domed wigwam, an Iroquois longhouse, a Creek council house, and other eastern woodland dwelling styles.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As of January 2024, the Hall of Eastern Woodlands Indians, along with the Hall of the Plains Indians, is closed to ensure compliance with new NAGPRA regulations.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Anne and Bernard Spitzer Hall of Human Origins, formerly The Hall of Human Biology and Evolution, is on the south side of the first floor, near the western end of the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It opened under its current name on February 10, 2007.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] When it first opened in 1921, the hall was known as the "Hall of the Age of Man", the only major exhibition in the United States to present an in-depth investigation of human evolution.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The displays traced the story of *Homo sapiens*, illuminated the path of human evolution and examined the origins of human creativity.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Many of the displays from the original hall can still be viewed in the present expanded format.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] These include life-size dioramas of human predecessors *Australopithecus afarensis*, *Homo ergaster*, Neanderthal, and Cro-Magnon, showing each species demonstrating the behaviors and capabilities that scientists believe they were capable of.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Also displayed are full-sized casts of important fossils, including the 3.2-million-year-old Lucy skeleton and the 1.7-million-year-old Turkana Boy, and *Homo erectus* specimens including a cast of Peking Man.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall also features replicas of ice age art found in the Dordogne region of southwestern France.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The limestone carvings of horses were made nearly 26,000 years ago and are considered to represent some of the earliest artistic expression of humans.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Arthur Ross Hall of Meteorites is on the southwest corner of the first floor.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It contains some of the finest specimens in the world including Ahnighito, a section of the 200-ton Cape York meteorite which was first made known to non-Inuit cultures on their investigation of Meteorite Island, Greenland.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Its great weight, 34 tons, makes it the largest displayed in the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It has support by columns that extend through the floor and into the bedrock below the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall also contains extra-solar nanodiamonds (diamonds with dimensions on the nanometer level) more than 5 billion years old.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] These were extracted from a meteorite sample through chemical means, and they are so small that a quadrillion of these fit into a volume smaller than a cubic centimeter.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Allison and Roberto Mignone Halls of Gems and Minerals (formerly the **Harry Frank Guggenheim Hall of Gems and Minerals**) is on the first floor, north of the Ross Hall of Meteorites.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It houses thousands of rare gems, minerals specimens and pieces of jewelry.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The halls closed in 2017 to undergo a $32 million redesign by Ralph Appelbaum Associates and reopened to the general public in June 2021.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The redesigned exhibits adopt newer philosophies in exhibit design, including a focus on storytelling, interactivity, and connecting ideas across disciplines.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The halls explore a range of topics, including the diversification of mineral species over the course of Earth's history, plate tectonics, and the stories of specific gems.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The halls display rare samples chosen from among the more than 100,000 pieces in the museum's collection including the Star of India, the Patricia Emerald, and the DeLong Star Ruby.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Gottesman Hall of Planet Earth is on the first floor at the northeast corner of the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Opened in 1999, it is a permanent hall devoted to the history of Earth, from accretion to the origin of life and contemporary human impacts on the planet.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall was designed to answer five key questions: "How has earth evolved?
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Why are there ocean basins, continents and mountains?
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Why is earth habitable?" The hall features rocks and other objects collected over 28 expeditions; the oldest rock is 4.3 billion years old, while the youngest was collected from a volcano on the day that it solidified.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] There is also a 30-seat granite amphitheater, with a globe, at the center of the hall.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Several sections also discuss the studies of Earth systems, including geology, glaciology, atmospheric sciences, and volcanology.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The exhibit has several large, touchable rock specimens.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The hall features striking samples of banded iron and deformed conglomerate rocks, as well as granites, sandstones, lavas, and three black smokers.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The north section of the hall, which deals primarily with plate tectonics, is arranged to mimic the Earth's structure, with the core and mantle at the center and crustal features on the perimeter.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Most of the museum's collections of mammalian and dinosaur fossils remain hidden from public view and are kept in many repositories deep within the museum complex.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The most significant storage facility among these is the ten-story Childs Frick Building, which started construction in 1969 and was completed in 1973.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] When the Frick Building was completed, the museum's collection of fossilized mammals and dinosaurs was the world's largest such collection, weighing 600 short tons (540 long tons; 540 t).
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Frick Building's top three floors contain laboratories and offices.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Other areas of the museum contain repositories of life from the past.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Whale Bone Storage Room is a cavernous space in which powerful winches come down from the ceiling to move the giant fossil bones about.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum attic upstairs includes even more storage facilities, such as the Elephant Room, while the tusk vault and boar vault are downstairs from the attic.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The great fossil collections that are open to public view occupy the entire fourth floor of the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The fourth floor exhibits are accessed by the Miriam and Ira D.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Wallach Orientation Center, which opened in 1996.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On the 77th Street side of the museum the visitor begins in the Orientation Center and follows a carefully marked path, which takes the visitor along an evolutionary tree of life.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As the tree "branches" the visitor is presented with the familial relationships among vertebrates, called cladograms.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A video projection on the museum's fourth floor introduces visitors to the concept of the cladogram.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Many of the fossils on display represent unique and historic pieces that were collected during the museum's golden era of worldwide expeditions (1880s–1930s).
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On a smaller scale, expeditions continue into the present and have resulted in additions to the collections from Vietnam, Madagascar, South America, and central and eastern Africa.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The first dinosaur hall in the museum opened in 1905.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The dinosaur halls were temporarily closed for renovation starting in 1990.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The first halls to reopen were the primitive-mammal and advanced-mammal halls, part of the Lila Acheson Wallace Wing of Mammals and Their Extinct Relatives, which opened in 1994.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Halls of Saurischian Dinosaurs and Ornithischian Dinosaurs reopened in 1995 as part of a $12 million expansion.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hall of Vertebrate Origins opened in 1996.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A *Triceratops* and a *Stegosaurus* (nicknamed Apex) are also both on display, among many other specimens.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Besides the fossils in museum display, many specimens are stored in the collections available for scientists.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Those include important specimens such as complete diplodocid skull, tyrannosaurid teeth, sauropod vertebrae, and many holotypes.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Hayden Planetarium, connected to the museum, is now part of the Rose Center for Earth and Space on the north side of the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The original Hayden Planetarium was founded in 1933 with a donation by philanthropist Charles Hayden, and it opened in 1935.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH announced the modern Rose Center for Earth and Space in early 1995, and demolition began the same year.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Frederick Phineas and Sandra Priest Rose Center for Earth and Space was completed in 2000 at a cost of $210 million.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Designed by James Stewart Polshek, the new building consists of a six-story high glass cube enclosing an 87 ft (27 m) illuminated sphere that appears to float, although it is actually supported by truss work.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Polshek has referred to his work as a "cosmic cathedral".
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The sphere is known as the Space Theater.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The facility encloses 333,500 sq ft (30,980 m2) of research, education, and exhibition space as well as the Hayden planetarium.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Also in the facility is the Department of Astrophysics, the newest academic research department in the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Neil DeGrasse Tyson is the director of the Hayden Planetarium.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In addition, Polshek designed the 1,800 sq ft (170 m2) Weston Pavilion, a 43 ft (13 m) high transparent structure of "water white" glass along the museum's west facade.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] This structure, a small companion piece to the Rose Center, offers a new entry way to the museum as well as opening further exhibition space for astronomically related objects.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Heilbrun Cosmic Pathway is one of the most popular exhibits in the Rose Center.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Designed by Studio Gang and landscape architects Reed Hilderbrand, the Richard Gilder Center for Science, Education and Innovation opened in May 2023.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The 230,000-square-foot addition includes six floors above ground, and one below.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Gilder Center welcomes visitors with a new, accessible entrance on Columbus Avenue that connects to central five-story atrium and creates more than 30 connections to the existing museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The atrium's architecture, described as cavern or canyon-like, is informed by natural processes like the movement of wind and water that shape geological landscapes.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] To achieve the continuous visual form, the atrium is constructed with shotcrete.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The curvilinear façade contrasts with the earlier High Victorian Gothic, Richardson Romanesque, and Beaux Arts structures, but its Milford Pink granite cladding is the same stone used on the Museum's west side.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Richard Gilder Center houses new exhibition and display areas devoted to insects, including an insectarium and butterfly vivarium, where visitors can walk among hundreds of live specimens as they flutter about in a lush tropical setting.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It also includes a visible storage structure that houses and displays scientific specimens; an expanded research library; classrooms and education areas, and laboratories.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] This expansion was originally supposed to be north of the existing museum, occupying parts of Theodore Roosevelt Park.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The expansion was relocated to the west side of the existing museum, and its footprint was reduced in size, due to opposition to construction in the park.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The annex replaced three existing buildings along Columbus Avenue's east side.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Founded in 1869, the AMNH Exhibitions Lab has since produced thousands of installations.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The department is notable for its integration of new scientific research into immersive art and multimedia presentations.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In addition to the famous dioramas at its home museum and the Rose Center for Earth and Space, the lab has also produced international exhibitions and software such as the Digital Universe Atlas.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The exhibitions team currently consists of over sixty artists, writers, preparators, designers and programmers.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The department is responsible for the creation of two to three exhibits per year.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] These extensive shows typically travel nationally to sister natural history museums.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] They have produced, among others, the first exhibits to discuss Darwinian evolution, human-induced climate change and the mesozoic mass extinction via asteroid.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Research Library is open to staff and public visitors, and is on the fourth floor of the museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The collection has many retrospective materials, some going back to the 15th century, that are difficult to find elsewhere.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In its early years, the Library expanded its collection mostly through such gifts as John Clarkson Jay's conchological library, Carson Brevoort's library on fishes and general zoology, Daniel Giraud Elliot's ornithological library, S.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Lowell Elliot's collection of books and pamphlets on various subjects, Harry Edwards's entomological library, the Hugh Jewett collection of voyages and travel, and Jules Marcou's geology collection.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In the 1900s, the library continued to grow with donations from figures and organizations such as Egbert Viele, the American Ethnological Society, Joel Asaph Allen, Hermon Carey Bumpus, and Henry Fairfield Osborn.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The new Library was designed by the firm Roche-Dinkeloo in 1992.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The space is 55,000 sq ft (5,100 m2) and includes five different "conservation zones", including the 50-person reading room, public offices, and temperature- and humidity-controlled rooms.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Today, the Library's collections contain over 550,000 volumes of monographs, serials, pamphlets, reprints, microforms, and original illustrations, as well as film, photographic, archives and manuscripts, fine art, memorabilia and rare book collections.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum has a scientific staff of more than 225, and sponsors over 120 special field expeditions each year.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Examples of some of these expeditions, financed in whole or part by the AMNH are: Jesup North Pacific Expedition, the Whitney South Seas Expedition, the Roosevelt–Rondon Scientific Expedition, the Crocker Land Expedition, and the expeditions to Madagascar and New Guinea by Richard Archbold.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On a smaller scale, expeditions continue into the present.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum also publishes several peer-reviewed journals, including the *Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History*.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH operates a biological field station in Portal, Arizona, among the Chiricahua Mountains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The Southwestern Research Station was established in 1955, purchased with a grant from philanthropist David Rockefeller, and with entomologist Mont Cazier as its first director.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The station, in a "biodiversity hotspot", is used by researchers and students, and offers occasional seminars to the public.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] AMNH's education programs include outreach to schools in New York City by the Moveable Museum.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH offers a wide variety of educational programs, camps, and classes for students from pre-K to post-graduate levels.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH sponsors the Lang Science Program, a comprehensive 5th–12th grade research and science education program, and the Science Research Mentorship Program (SRMP), in which pairs of students conduct a full year of intensive original research with an AMNH scientist.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] As of 2023, about 400,000 schoolchildren annually take field trips to the AMNH.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Although most students visit for a day or less, since late 2023 the museum has also provided a weeklong educational program called Beyond Elementary Explorations in Science.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On October 23, 2006, the museum launched the Richard Gilder Graduate School, becoming the first American museum in the United States to award doctoral degrees in its own name.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The school is named for businessman Richard Gilder, who contributed $50 million toward the school.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Accredited in 2009, the school had 11 students enrolled in 2011, who work closely with curators and have access to the collections.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The first seven graduates were awarded their degrees in 2013.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The AMNH offers a Master of Arts in Teaching (MAT) in Earth Science and a PhD in Comparative Biology.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The MAT Earth Science Residency program was launched in 2012 to address a critical shortage of qualified science teachers in New York state.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In 2015, the MAT program officially joined the Richard Gilder Graduate School, with the NYS Board of Regents authorizing the Gilder School to grant the MAT degree.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum's first three presidents were all cofounders.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Jesup (1881–1908), bequeathed $1 million to the museum upon his death.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Langdon Jr., (1987–1993) the first president to receive a salary; all previous presidents had served without pay.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The fourth president, Henry Fairfield Osborn, appointed on the death of Jesup, consolidated the museum's expansion and developed it further.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Under Osborn, the museum embraced a growing eugenics movement.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Osborn's friend, noted eugenicist Madison Grant, a member of the museum's executive committee, was the author of the 1916 book, The Passing of the Great Race.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] He also was a funder and shaper of the 1921 Second International Congress of Eugenics, held at the museum**.** Noted eugenicist Charles Davenport presided over the 1932 Third International Eugenics Congress. at the museum as well.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Rice Jr.; and ornithologist Robert Cushman Murphy.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum is at 79th Street and Central Park West.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] There is a direct entrance into the museum from the New York City Subway's 81st Street–Museum of Natural History station, served by the B and C trains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On a pedestal outside the museum's Columbus Avenue entrance is a stainless steel time capsule, which was created after a design competition that was won by Santiago Calatrava.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The capsule was sealed at the beginning of 2000, to mark the beginning of the 3rd millennium.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] It takes the form of a folded saddle-shaped volume, symmetrical on multiple axes, that explores formal properties of folded spherical frames.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The capsule is to be opened in the year 3000.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The museum is in a 17-acre (69,000 m2) city park known as **Theodore Roosevelt Park** that extends from Central Park West to Columbus Avenue, and from West 77th to 81st Streets and that contains park benches, gardens and lawns, and also a dog run.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] On the west side of the park, between 80th and 81st Streets near Columbus Avenue, is the Nobel Monument honoring Nobel Prize winners from the United States.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Having visited the museum, Dabashi reflected on the juxtaposition of scientific progress and what he sees as the persistent legacy of racism in the United States.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The statue of Theodore Roosevelt is seen by Dabashi as a symbol of racial hierarchy and the ongoing struggle to reconcile the nation's past with its present.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] The statue would later be removed in 2022, as a consequence of discussions about racism aroused by the 2020 protests surrounding the murder of George Floyd.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] A 2020 article by University of New Hampshire historian Julia Rodriguez contrasts the approaches respectively taken by the AMNH and the Musée de l'Homme in Paris, in terms of their human and cultural exhibits.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] While Rodriguez criticizes the AMNH's exhibits for their failure to acknowledge colonial histories, the Musée de l'Homme has made strides in decolonizing its displays.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Rodriguez also posits that notably absent from such museums are exhibits dedicated to Northern European or New England cultures, suggesting a biased focus on "othering" non-Western societies while normalizing Western cultural norms.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In a June 2024 essay published in Indian online paper ThePrint, Stanford University history professor Priya Satia argues that the museum's Hall of Asian Peoples is problematic because it portrays Asian cultures as static and frozen in time.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Satia believes various misrepresentations can lead to misunderstandings and perpetuate harmful biases against Asian and Middle Eastern people.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] In the same essay, Satia also delves into parts of the museum's own history, such as its 1921 hosting of the Second International Eugenics Congress.
[src:eleanora-knopf/american-museum-of-natural-history-p02] Her essay was criticized by Samuel Abrams, who serves as a Nonresident Senior Fellow of the American Enterprise Institute, as a researcher at NYU, and as a Professor of Politics at Sarah Lawrence College.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Anna was the only child to George and Mary Hughes Gilbert Jonas and grew up in Bridgeton, New Jersey.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Her parents ran a family-owned business called the Williamstown Glass Company where she worked during World War I as a cashier.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Anna was known to be fond of her ancestry that included relatives who emigrated from New England to Cape May in the 1690s.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Her lineage is made of relatives who were plantation owners in Cape May, whalers, and Delaware River Pilots.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] She began her mapping in Southeastern Pennsylvania and Maryland.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Then on, she began her mapping Southwestward into the crystalline rocks of Virginia to North Carolina afterwards.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] In 1938, Anna married George Willis Stose who worked as a U.S.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] G.S. stratigrapher and would end up working by her side on the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Anna received formal education from Bryn Mawr College and earned her A.D in 1904.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] In 1905, she earned her A.M, and then her PhD in 1912.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Furthermore, she had an education major in the Arts.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Throughout her college career, Anna had the opportunity to work under tenured female geologists, who she would continue to work with closely after graduating from college.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] From 1908 to 1909, she was an assistant curator at the Geology Museum and worked extensively in the geology laboratories during college.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Her classmates included Eleanora Knopf and Julia Gardner, and she mentored under Florence Bascom, one of the pioneer women of geology.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Between 1916 and 1917, she began work at the Department of Geology, following that she worked at the American Museum of Natural History.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Anna contributed to geology simply by being a woman during a time when women faced prejudices for being active in such a field.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] In her professional career as a geologist, Anna was known to be very outspoken.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] During Anna's long career in the scientific community, she made numerous geological contributions, including identification of structural characteristics and trends by using maps that she printed in colour.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Instead of creating 5 by 6 quadrangle maps, Anna's work was focused on creating larger scaled maps.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Working with Eleanora Knopf, Anna helped defined the Martic Line.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] They believed it to be a major thrust fault in Pennsylvania.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Her ideas were often considered to be incomprehensible by other geologists at the time, as her work was far too advanced.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Being a female in this time also caused scientists to often disregard or overlook her ideas.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] The Piedmont and Blue Ridge provinces in the southern and central Appalachians were the locations where Anna's studies led her to one of her greatest achievements.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Throughout her research over the Appalachian Mountains, Anna worked alongside her husband George W.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Stose, and many of their findings were published together.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Crystalline rock makes up the southern Appalachian Mountains and was mobile during the Precambrian and again during the Paleozoic era.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] During this time, there was intense crustal folding and intrusion to the rock formation.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Once the crust folding ceased, granite rock carved through the inner part of the mountain range.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Anna's publications spanned sixty years.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] In 1905, she published her first paper, it focused on the rocks of the crystalline Appalachians.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] In 1965, she published her last paper that described the cataloging of lithologies, and the potential origins of 18th-century tombstones in old cemeteries located in Cape May County, New Jersey.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] In her last paper she also noted that the correlation of certain rocks dated back to Early Paleozoic rocks.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Anna was the first person to interpret the Brevard Zone rocks as having formed along a thrust fault.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Afterwards, contrary to Stose's interpretation, other geologists saw the Brevard Zone was actually the trace of a large strike-slip fault.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] For many years, this idea obtained widespread acceptance, but at the present time, Stose's explanation is believed to be more accurate.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] In a book called Studies of Appalachian Geology: Central and Southern, which was published in 1970 and edited by George Fisher, Stose is the geologist with the most listings in the author index.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Stose and her husband, George Stose, compiled county wide reports such as the "New Holland quadrangle" (Jonas and Stose, 1926), "Geology and Mineral Resources of York County" (Stose and Jonas, 1939), "Middletowne quadrangle" (Stose and Jonas, 1933).
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] These reports laid the foundation for southeastern Pennsylvanian geology.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] In 1944, the couple wrote a report on the Geology of the Hanover-York District (published by the U.S.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] This is their only work that is formally listed as Stose and Stose, and is still acknowledged by today's geologists due to the advanced explanations and illustrations contained within the publication.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Anna spent time working at the American Museum of Natural History throughout 1916 and 1917, she then worked as a geologist for the Maryland and Pennsylvania Geological Surveys between 1919 and 1937.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] She worked as a geologist two more times, firstly for the Virginia Geological Survey from 1926 to 1945, and secondly with the U.S.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Geological Survey from 1930 until her retirement in 1954.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Anna later died on October 27, 1974, due to a stroke, while George Stose died back in 1960.
[src:eleanora-knopf/anna-jonas-stose] Her work is still used today as a tribute of her contributions to field of geology in a time when women were not recognized.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The **Appalachian Mountains**, often called the **Appalachians**, are a mountain range in eastern to northeastern North America.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The term "Appalachian" refers to several different regions and mountain systems associated with the mountain range, and its surrounding terrain.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The general definition used is one followed by the United States Geological Survey and the Geological Survey of Canada to describe the respective countries' physiographic regions.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The U.S. uses the term Appalachian Highlands and Canada uses the term Appalachian Uplands; the Appalachian Mountains are not synonymous with the Appalachian Plateau, which is one of the seven provinces of the Appalachian Highlands.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The highest peak of the mountain range is Mount Mitchell in North Carolina at 6,684 feet (2,037 m), which is also the highest point in the United States east of the Mississippi River.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The range is older than the other major mountain range in North America, the Rocky Mountains of the west.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Some of the outcrops in the Appalachians contain rocks formed during the Precambrian.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The geologic processes that led to the formation of the Appalachian Mountains started 1.1 billion years ago.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The first mountain range in the region was created when the continents of Laurentia and Amazonia collided, creating a supercontinent called Rodinia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The collision of these continents caused the rocks to be folded and faulted, creating the first mountains in the region.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Many of the rocks and minerals that were formed during that event can currently be seen at the surface of the present Appalachian range.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Around 480 million years ago, geologic processes began that led to three distinct orogenic eras that created much of the surface structure seen in today's Appalachians.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] During this period, mountains once reached elevations similar to those of the Alps and the Rockies before natural erosion occurred over the last 240 million years leading to what is present today.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachian Mountains are a barrier to east–west travel, as they form a series of alternating ridgelines and valleys oriented in opposition to most highways and railroads running east–west.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] This barrier was extremely important in shaping the expansion of the United States in the colonial era.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The range is the home of a very popular recreational feature, the Appalachian Trail.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] This is a 2,175-mile (3,500 km) hiking trail that runs all the way from Mount Katahdin in Maine to Springer Mountain in Georgia, passing over or past a large part of the Appalachian range.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The International Appalachian Trail is an extension of this hiking trail into the Canadian portion of the Appalachian range in New Brunswick and Quebec.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The name was soon altered by the Spanish to Apalachee and used as a name for the tribe and region spreading well inland to the north.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Pánfilo de Narváez's expedition first entered Apalachee territory on June 15, 1528, and applied the name.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Now spelled "Appalachian", it is the fourth-oldest surviving European place-name in the US.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] After the 1540 expedition of Hernando de Soto, Spanish cartographers began to apply the name of the tribe to the mountains themselves.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The first cartographic appearance of *Apalchen* is on Diego Gutiérrez's map of 1562; the first use for the mountain range is the map of Jacques le Moyne de Morgues in 1565.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The name was not commonly used for the whole mountain range until the late 19th century.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] A competing and often more popular name was the "Allegheny Mountains", "Alleghenies", and even "Alleghania".
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In the early 19th century, Washington Irving proposed renaming the United States either Appalachia or Alleghania.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In U.S. dialects in most regions of the Appalachians, the word is pronounced /ˌæpəˈlætʃɪnz/, with the third syllable sounding like "latch".
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In some northern parts of the mountain range, particularly Pennsylvania, it is pronounced /ˌæpəˈleɪtʃɪnz/ or /ˌæpəˈleɪʃɪnz/; the third syllable is like "lay", and the fourth "chins" or "shins".
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] There is often great debate between the residents of the regions regarding the correct pronunciation.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Elsewhere, a commonly accepted pronunciation for the adjective *Appalachian* is /ˌæpəˈlætʃiən/, with the last two syllables "-ian" pronounced as in the word "Romanian".
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] However, each of the governments has an agency that informs the public about the major landforms that make up the countries, the United States Geological Survey (USGS) and the Geological Survey of Canada (GSC).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The landforms are referred to as physiographic regions.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The regions create precise boundaries from which maps can be drawn.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachian Highlands is the name of one of the eight physiographic regions of the contiguous 48 United States.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachian Uplands is the name of one of seven physiographic regions of Canada.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The second level in the physiographic classification schema for the USGS is "province", the same word as Canada uses to divide its political subdivisions, meaning that the terminology used by the two countries do not match below the region level.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The lowest level of classification is "section".
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachian Uplands are one of the seven physiographic divisions in Canada.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Canada's GSC does not use the same classification system as the USGS below the division level.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The agency does break the divisions of the Appalachian Uplands into 13 subsections that are in four different political provinces of Canada.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] While the Appalachian Highlands and Appalachian Uplands are generally continuous across the U.S./Canadian border, the St.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Lawrence Valley area is handled differently in the physiographic classification schemas.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Lawrence Valley in the United States is one of the second-level classifications, part of the Appalachian Highlands.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In Canada, the area is part of the first-level classification, the St.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] This includes the area around the city of Montreal, Anticosti Island, and the northwest coastline of Newfoundland.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The dissected plateau area, while not actually made up of geological mountains, is popularly called "mountains", especially in eastern Kentucky and West Virginia, and while the ridges are not high, the terrain is extremely rugged.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In Ohio and New York, some of the plateau has been glaciated, which has rounded off the sharp ridges and filled the valleys to some extent.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The glaciated regions are usually referred to as hill country rather than mountains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The mountain system has no axis of dominating altitudes, but in every portion, the summits rise to rather uniform heights, and, especially in the central section, the various ridges and intermontane valleys have the same trend as the system itself.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] None of the summits reaches the region of perpetual snow.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In Pennsylvania, there are over sixty summits that rise over 2,500 ft (800 m); the summits of Mount Davis and Blue Knob rise over 3,000 ft (900 m).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In Maryland, Eagle Rock and Dans Mountain are conspicuous points reaching 3,162 and 2,882 ft (964 and 878 m) respectively.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] On the same side of the Great Valley, south of the Potomac, are the Pinnacle 3,007 feet (917 m) and Pidgeon Roost 3,400 ft (1,000 m).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In West Virginia, more than 150 peaks rise above 4,000 ft (1,200 m), including Spruce Knob 4,863 ft (1,482 m), the highest point in the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] A number of other points in the state rise above 4,800 ft (1,500 m).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Cheat Mountain (Snowshoe Mountain) at Thorny Flat 4,848 ft (1,478 m) and Bald Knob 4,842 ft (1,476 m) are among the more notable peaks in West Virginia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Blue Ridge Mountains, rising in southern Pennsylvania and there known as South Mountain, attain elevations of about 2,000 ft (600 m) in Pennsylvania.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] South Mountain achieves its highest point just below the Mason-Dixon line in Maryland at Quirauk Mountain 2,145 ft (654 m) and then diminishes in height southward to the Potomac River.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Once in Virginia, the Blue Ridge again reaches 2,000 ft (600 m) and higher.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In the Virginia Blue Ridge, the following are some of the highest peaks north of the Roanoke River: Stony Man 4,031 ft (1,229 m), Hawksbill Mountain 4,066 ft (1,239 m), Apple Orchard Mountain 4,225 ft (1,288 m) and Peaks of Otter 4,001 and 3,875 ft (1,220 and 1,181 m).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] South of the Roanoke River, along the Blue Ridge, are Virginia's highest peaks including Whitetop Mountain 5,520 ft (1,680 m) and Mount Rogers 5,729 ft (1,746 m), the highest point in the Commonwealth.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Chief summits in the southern section of the Blue Ridge are located along two main crests, the Western or Unaka Front along the Tennessee-North Carolina border and the Eastern Front in North Carolina, or one of several "cross ridges" between the two main crests.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Prominent summits in the cross ridges include Waterrock Knob (6,292 ft (1,918 m)) in the Plott Balsams.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Across northern Georgia, numerous peaks exceed 4,000 ft (1,200 m), including Brasstown Bald, the state's highest, at 4,784-and-4,696 ft (1,458-and-1,431 m) Rabun Bald.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In north-central Alabama, Mount Cheaha rises prominently to 1,445 feet (440 m) over its surroundings, as part of the southernmost spur of the Blue Ridge Mountains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Plate tectonics over the period dating back at least 1 billion years led to geological creation of the land that is now the Appalachian Mountain range.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The continental movement led to collisions that built mountains and they later pulled apart creating oceans over parts of the continent that are now exposed.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The first mountain-building tectonic plate collision that initiated the construction of what are today the Appalachians occurred at least a billion years ago when the pre-North American craton called Laurentia collided with at least one other craton — Amazonia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] All the other cratons of the earth also collided at about this time to form the supercontinent Rodinia and were surrounded by one single ocean.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] (It is possible that the cratons of Kalahari, and Rio Plato, were also part of that early collision since they were present as Rodinia broke up).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Mountain-building referred to as the Grenville Orogeny occurred along the boundaries of the cratons.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The present Appalachian Mountains have at least two areas which are made from rock formations that were formed during this orogeny - the Blue Ridge Mountains and the Adirondacks.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] After the Grenville orogeny, the direction of the continental drift reversed, and the single supercontinent Rodinia began to break up.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The mountains formed during the Grenvillian era underwent erosion due to weathering, glaciation, and other natural processes, resulting in the leveling of the landscape.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The eroded sediments from these mountains contributed to the formation of sedimentary basins and valleys.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] For example, in what is now the southern United States, the Ococee Basin was formed.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Rivers from the surrounding countryside carried clay, silt, sand, and gravel to the basin, much as rivers today carry sediment from the midcontinent region to the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The sediment spread out in layers on the basin floor.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The basin continued to subside, and over a long period of time, probably millions of years, a great thickness of sediment accumulated.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Eventually, the tectonic forces pulling the two continents apart became so strong that an ocean formed off the eastern coast of the Laurentian margin.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] This was called the Iapetus Ocean and was the precursor of the modern Atlantic Ocean.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The rocks of the Valley and Ridge province formed over millions of years, in the Iapetus.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Shells and other hard parts of ancient marine plants and animals accumulated to form limey deposits that later became limestone.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] This is the same process by which limestone forms in modern oceans.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The weathering of limestone, now exposed at the land surface, produces the lime-rich soils that are so prevalent in the fertile farmland of the Valley and Ridge province.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] During this continental break-up, around 600 million to 560 million years ago, volcanic activity was present along the tectonic margins.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] There is evidence of this activity in today's Blue Ridge Mountains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Mount Rogers, Whitetop Mountain, and Pine Mountain are all the result of volcanic activity that occurred around this time.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Evidence of subsurface activity, dikes and sills intruding into the overlying rock, is present in the Blue Ridge as well.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] For instance, mafic rocks have been found along the Fries Fault in the central Blue Ridge area of Montgomery County, Virginia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] One of the best examples of mafic rocks from the breakup of Rodina is the Catoctin Formation.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Erupted during the final stages of rifting associated with Rodinia (570-550 Ma), these rocks where later metamorphosed into Greenstone.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Iapetus continued to expand and during that time bacteria, algae, and many species of invertebrates flourished in the oceans, but there were no plants or animals on land.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Then, during the middle Ordovician Period about 500 to 470 million years ago, the motion of the crustal plates changed, and the continents began to move back toward each other.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The once-quiet Appalachian passive margin changed to a very active plate boundary when a neighboring Iapetus oceanic plate containing a volcanic arc collided with and began sinking beneath the North American craton.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Volcanoes grew along the continental margin coincident with the initiation of subduction.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Thrust faulting uplifted and warped older sedimentary rock laid down on the passive margin.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] As the mountains rose, erosion began to wear them down over time.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Streams carried rock debris downslope to be deposited in nearby lowlands.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Taconic orogeny ended after about 60 million years, but built much of the land mass that is now New England and southwestward to Pennsylvania.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Taconic Orogeny was the second of four mountain building plate collisions that contributed to the formation of the Appalachians, culminating in the collision of North America and Africa (see Alleghanian orogeny).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The third mountain-building event was the Acadian orogeny which occurred between 375 and 359 million years ago.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Acadian orogeny was caused by a series of collisions of pieces of crust from the Avalonia Terrane, sections broken off from continent of Gondwana, with the North American Plate.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The collision initiating this orogeny resulted in the closing of the southern Iapetus Ocean and the formation of a high mountain belt.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] After the Acadian collision took place, Gondwana began to retreat from Laurentia with the newly accreted Avalonian terranes left behind.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] As Gondwana moved away, a new ocean opened up, the Rheic Ocean, during the Middle to Late Devonian, and subsequently its closure would result in the formation of the Alleghanian orogeny.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] As the continental plates moved closer together, fragments of oceanic crust, islands, and other continental masses collided with the eastern margin of ancestral North America.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] By this time, plants had appeared on land, followed by scorpions, insects, and amphibians.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The ocean continued to shrink until, about 270 million years ago, the continents that were ancestral to North America and Africa collided during the formation of the supercontinent Pangea.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Because North America and Africa were once geographically connected, the Appalachians formed part of the same mountain chain as the Little Atlas in Morocco.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] This mountain range, known as the Central Pangean Mountains, extended into Scotland, before the Mesozoic Era opening of the Iapetus Ocean, from the North America/Europe collision (See Caledonian orogeny).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] By the end of the Mesozoic Era, the Appalachian Mountains had been eroded to an almost flat plain.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] It was not until the region was uplifted during the Cenozoic Era that the distinctive topography of the present formed.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Uplift rejuvenated the streams, which rapidly responded by cutting downward into the ancient bedrock.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Some streams flowed along weak layers that define the folds and faults created many millions of years earlier.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Other streams downcut so rapidly that they cut right across the resistant folded rocks of the mountain core, carving canyons across rock layers and geologic structures.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachian Mountains contain major deposits of anthracite coal as well as bituminous coal.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In the folded mountains the coal is in metamorphosed form as anthracite, represented by the Coal Region of northeastern Pennsylvania.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The bituminous coal fields of western Pennsylvania, western Maryland, southeastern Ohio, eastern Kentucky, southwestern Virginia, and West Virginia contain the sedimentary form of coal.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The mountain top removal method of coal mining, in which entire mountain tops are removed, is currently threatening vast areas and ecosystems of the Appalachian Mountain region.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The surface coal mining that started in the 1940s has significantly impacted the central Appalachian Mountains in Kentucky, Tennessee, Virginia and West Virginia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Early mining methods were unregulated and mined land reclamation research, including acid base accounting, was led by the West Virginia University in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] West Virginia developed rigorous mine reclamation standards for state coal mines in the late 1960s.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Regulations were introduced by most states to protect the Appalachian Mountains by the late 1960s.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Social and political activism brought about the Surface Mining Control and Reclamation Act of 1977.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The 1859 discovery of commercial quantities of petroleum in the Appalachian Mountains of western Pennsylvania started the modern United States petroleum industry.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Recent discoveries of commercial natural gas deposits in the Marcellus Shale formation and Utica Shale formations have once again focused oil industry attention on the Appalachian Basin.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Some plateaus of the Appalachian Mountains contain metallic minerals such as iron and zinc.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] There are many geological issues concerning the rivers and streams of the Appalachians.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In spite of the existence of the Great Appalachian Valley, many of the main rivers are transverse to the mountain system axis.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The drainage divide of the Appalachians follows a tortuous course that crosses the mountainous belt just north of the New River in Virginia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In the northern section, the height of land lies on the inland side of the mountainous belt, and thus the main lines of drainage run from north to south, exemplified by the Hudson River.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] However, the valley through which the Hudson River flows was cut by the gigantic glaciers of the ice ages—the same glaciers that deposited their terminal moraines in southern New York and formed the east–west Long Island.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachian region is generally considered the geographical divide between the eastern seaboard of the United States and the Midwest region of the country.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Eastern Continental Divide follows the Appalachian Mountains from Pennsylvania to Georgia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachians, particularly the Central and Southern regions, is one of the most biodiverse places in North America.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The north–south orientation of the long ridges and valleys contributes to the high number of plant and animal species.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Species were able to migrate through these from either direction during alternating periods of warming and cooling, settling in the microclimates that best suited them.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The flora of the Appalachians are diverse and vary primarily in response to geology, latitude, elevation and moisture availability.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Geobotanically, they constitute a floristic province of the North American Atlantic Region.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachians consist primarily of deciduous broad-leaf trees and evergreen needle-leaf conifers, but also contain the evergreen broad-leaf American holly (*Ilex opaca*), and the deciduous needle-leaf conifer, the tamarack, or eastern larch (*Larix laricina*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The dominant northern and high elevation conifer is the red spruce (*Picea rubens*), which grows from near sea level to above 4,000 ft (1,200 m) above sea level (asl) in northern New England and southeastern Canada.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] It also grows southward along the Appalachian crest to the highest elevations of the southern Appalachians, as in North Carolina and Tennessee.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In the central Appalachians it is usually confined above 3,000 ft (900 m) asl, except for a few cold valleys in which it reaches lower elevations.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In the southern Appalachians, it is restricted to higher elevations.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Another species is the black spruce (*Picea mariana*), which extends farthest north of any conifer in North America, is found at high elevations in the northern Appalachians, and in bogs as far south as Pennsylvania.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachians are also home to two species of fir, the boreal balsam fir (*Abies balsamea*), and the southern high elevation endemic, Fraser fir (*Abies fraseri*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Fraser fir is endemic to the highest parts of the southern Appalachian Mountains, where along with red spruce it forms a fragile ecosystem known as the Southern Appalachian spruce–fir forest.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Fraser fir rarely occurs below 5,500 ft (1,700 m), and becomes the dominant tree type at 6,200 ft (1,900 m).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] By contrast, balsam fir is found from near sea level to the tree line in the northern Appalachians, but ranges only as far south as Virginia and West Virginia in the central Appalachians, where it is usually confined above 3,900 ft (1,200 m) asl, except in cold valleys.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Curiously, it is associated with oaks in Virginia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The balsam fir of Virginia and West Virginia is thought by some to be a natural hybrid between the more northern variety and Fraser fir.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] While red spruce is common in both upland and bog habitats, balsam fir, as well as black spruce and tamarack, are more characteristic of the latter.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] However, balsam fir also does well in soils with a pH as high as 6.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Eastern or Canada hemlock (*Tsuga canadensis*) is another important evergreen needle-leaf conifer that grows along the Appalachian chain from north to south but is confined to lower elevations than red spruce and the firs.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] It generally occupies richer and less acidic soils than the spruce and firs and is characteristic of deep, shaded and moist mountain valleys and coves.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] It is subject to the hemlock woolly adelgid (*Adelges tsugae*), an introduced insect, that is rapidly extirpating it as a forest tree.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Less abundant, and restricted to the southern Appalachians, is Carolina hemlock (*Tsuga caroliniana*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Like Canada hemlock, this tree suffers severely from the hemlock woolly adelgid.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Several species of pines characteristic of the Appalachians are eastern white pine (*Pinus strobus*), Virginia pine (*Pinus virginiana*), pitch pine (*Pinus rigida*), Table Mountain pine (*Pinus pungens*) and shortleaf pine (*Pinus echinata*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Red pine (*Pinus resinosa*) is a boreal species that forms a few high elevation outliers as far south as West Virginia.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] All of these species except white pine tend to occupy sandy, rocky, poor soil sites, which are mostly acidic in character.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] White pine, a large species valued for its timber, tends to do best in rich, moist soil, either acidic or alkaline in character.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Pitch pine is also at home in acidic, boggy soil, and Table Mountain pine may occasionally be found in this habitat as well.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Shortleaf pine is generally found in warmer habitats and at lower elevations than the other species.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] All the species listed do best in open or lightly shaded habitats, although white pine also thrives in shady coves, valleys, and on floodplains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachians are characterized by a wealth of large, beautiful deciduous broadleaf (hardwood) trees.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Their occurrences are best summarized and described in E.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Lucy Braun's 1950 classic, *Deciduous Forests of Eastern North America* (Macmillan, New York).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The most diverse and richest forests are the mixed-mesophytic or medium-moisture types, which are largely confined to rich, moist montane soils of the southern and central Appalachians, particularly in the Cumberland and Allegheny Mountains, but also thrive in the southern Appalachian coves.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Characteristic canopy species are white basswood (*Tilia heterophylla*), yellow buckeye (*Aesculus octandra*), sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*), American beech (*Fagus grandifolia*), tuliptree (*Liriodendron tulipifera*), white ash (*Fraxinus americana*) and yellow birch (*Betula alleganiensis*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Other common trees are red maple (*Acer rubrum*), shagbark and bitternut hickories (*Carya ovata* and *C. cordiformis*) and black or sweet birch (*Betula lenta*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Small understory trees and shrubs include paw paw (*Asimina tribola*), flowering dogwood (*Cornus florida*), hophornbeam (*Ostrya virginiana*), witch-hazel (*Hamamelis virginiana*) and spicebush (*Lindera benzoin*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] There are also hundreds of perennial and annual herbs, among them such herbal and medicinal plants as American ginseng (*Panax quinquefolius*), goldenseal (*Hydrastis canadensis*), bloodroot (*Sanguinaria canadensis*) and black cohosh (*Cimicifuga racemosa*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The foregoing trees, shrubs, and herbs are also more widely distributed in less rich mesic forests that generally occupy coves, stream valleys and flood plains throughout the southern and central Appalachians at low and intermediate elevations.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Drier and rockier uplands and ridges are occupied by oak–chestnut forests dominated by a variety of oaks (*Quercus* spp.), hickories (*Carya* spp.) and, in the past, by the American chestnut (*Castanea dentata*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The American chestnut was virtually eliminated as a canopy species by the introduced fungal chestnut blight (*Cryphonectaria parasitica*), but lives on as sapling-sized sprouts that originate from roots, which are not killed by the fungus.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In present-day forest canopies, chestnut has been largely replaced by oaks.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The oak forests of the southern and central Appalachians consist largely of black, northern red, white, chestnut and scarlet oaks (*Quercus velutina*, *Q. rubra*, *Q. alba*, *Q. prinus* and *Q. coccinea*) and hickories, such as the pignut (*Carya glabra*) in particular.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The richest forests, which grade into mesic types, usually in coves and on gentle slopes, have predominantly white and northern red oaks, while the driest sites are dominated by chestnut oak, or sometimes by scarlet or northern red oaks.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In the northern Appalachians the oaks, except for white and northern red, drop out, while the latter extends farthest north.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The oak forests generally lack the diverse small tree, shrub and herb layers of mesic forests.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The evergreen great rhododendron (*Rhododendron maximum*) is characteristic of moist stream valleys.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] These occurrences are in line with the prevailing acidic character of most oak forest soils.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In contrast, the much rarer chinquapin oak (*Quercus muehlenbergii*) demands alkaline soils and generally grows where limestone rock is near the surface.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Hence no ericaceous shrubs are associated with it.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The Appalachian flora also include a diverse assemblage of bryophytes (mosses and liverworts), as well as fungi.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] As with vascular plants, these tend to be closely related to the character of the soils and the thermal environment in which they are found.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Eastern deciduous forests are subject to a number of serious insect and disease outbreaks.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Among the most conspicuous is that of the introduced spongy moth (*Lymantria dispar*), which infests primarily oaks, causing severe defoliation and tree mortality.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] But it also has the benefit of eliminating weak individuals, and thus improving the genetic stock, as well as creating rich habitat of a type through accumulation of dead wood.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Because hardwoods sprout so readily, this moth is not as harmful as the hemlock woolly adelgid.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Perhaps more serious is the introduced beech bark disease complex, which includes both a scale insect (*Cryptococcus fagisuga*) and fungal components.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] During the 19th and early 20th centuries, the Appalachian forests were subject to severe and destructive logging and land clearing, which resulted in the designation of the national forests and parks as well many state-protected areas.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] However, these and a variety of other destructive activities continue, albeit in diminished forms; and thus far only a few ecologically based management practices have taken hold.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Appalachian bogs are boreal ecosystems, which occur in many places in the Appalachians, particularly the Allegheny and Blue Ridge subranges.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Though popularly called bogs, many of them are technically fens.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Several mountain summits in the southern Appalachians are covered with expansive open habitats (either grassy meadows or heath) known as Appalachian balds.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] These habitats support many unique plant and animal communities, including rare, relict species, that are adapted to the open, exposed habitat.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Others, especially those dominated by introduced grasses, may be fully anthropogenic in origin.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The abandonment of grazing has caused trees to encroach on many of these balds, threatening their ecosystems.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Animals that characterize the Appalachian forests include five species of tree squirrels.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The most commonly seen is the low to moderate elevation eastern gray squirrel (*Sciurus carolinensis*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Occupying similar habitat is the slightly larger fox squirrel (*Sciurus niger*) and the much smaller southern flying squirrel (*Glaucomys volans*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] As familiar as squirrels are the eastern cottontail rabbit (*Silvilagus floridanus*) and the white-tailed deer (*Odocoileus virginianus*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The latter in particular has greatly increased in abundance as a result of the extirpation of the eastern wolf (*Canis lupus lycaon*) and the North American cougar.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] This has led to the overgrazing and browsing of many plants of the Appalachian forests, as well as destruction of agricultural crops.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Other deer include the moose (*Alces alces*), found only in the north, and the elk (*Cervus canadensis*), which, although once extirpated, is now making a comeback, through transplantation, in the southern and central Appalachians.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] In Quebec, the Chic-Chocs host the only population of reindeer (*Rangifer tarandus*) south of the St.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] An additional species that is common in the north but extends its range southward at high elevations to Virginia and West Virginia is the varying or snowshoe hare (*Lepus americanus*).
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] However, these central Appalachian populations are scattered and very small.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Another species of great interest is the beaver (*Castor canadensis*), which is showing a great resurgence in numbers after its near extirpation for its pelt.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] This resurgence is bringing about a drastic alteration in habitat through the construction of dams and other structures throughout the mountains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] European boars (*Sus scrofa*) were introduced in the early 20th century.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Of great importance are the many species of salamanders and, in particular, the lungless species (family Plethodontidae) that live in great abundance concealed by leaves and debris, on the forest floor.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Most frequently seen, however, is the eastern or red-spotted newt (*Notophthalmus viridescens*), whose terrestrial eft form is often encountered on the open, dry forest floor.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] It has been estimated that salamanders represent the largest class of animal biomass in the Appalachian forests.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Frogs and toads are of lesser diversity and abundance, but the wood frog (*Rana sylvatica*) is, like the eft, commonly encountered on the dry forest floor, while a number of species of small frogs, such as spring peepers (*Pseudacris crucifer*), enliven the forest with their calls.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Salamanders and other amphibians contribute greatly to nutrient cycling through their consumption of small life forms on the forest floor and in aquatic habitats.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Although reptiles are less abundant and diverse than amphibians, a number of snakes are conspicuous members of the fauna.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] One of the largest is the non-venomous black rat snake (*Elaphe obsoleta obsoleta*), while the common garter snake (*Thamnophis sirtalis*) is among the smallest but most abundant.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The eastern copperhead (*Agkistrodon contortrix*) and the timber rattler (*Crotalus horridus*) are venomous pit vipers.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] There are few lizards, but the broad-headed skink (*Eumeces laticeps*), at up to 13 in (33 cm) in length, and an excellent climber and swimmer, is one of the largest and most spectacular in appearance and action.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] The most common turtle is the eastern box turtle (*Terrapene carolina carolina*), which is found in both upland and lowland forests in the central and southern Appalachians.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Prominent among aquatic species is the large common snapping turtle (*Chelydra serpentina*), which occurs throughout the Appalachians.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Appalachian streams are notable for their highly diverse freshwater fish life.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Among the most abundant and diverse are those of the minnow family (family Cyprinidae), while species of the colorful darters (*Percina* spp.) are also abundant.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] A characteristic fish of shaded, cool Appalachian forest streams is the wild brook or speckled trout (*Salvelinus fontinalis*), which is much sought after as a game fish.
[src:eleanora-knopf/appalachians] Water Striders (family *Gerridae*) are insects commonly seen on the surface of calm streams and ponds.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] Atherosclerosis is the primary cause of coronary artery disease (CAD) and stroke, with multiple genetic and environmental contributions.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] Genetic-epidemiologic studies have identified many genetic and non-genetic risk factors for CAD.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] However, such studies indicate that family history is the most significant independent risk factor.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] The signs and symptoms of arteriosclerosis depend on the vessel affected by the disease.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] If affecting cerebral or ophthalmic vessels, as in cerebrovascular accidents or transient ischemic attacks, signs and symptoms may include sudden weakness, facial or lower limb numbness, confusion, difficulty understanding speech, and problems seeing.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] If affecting coronary vessels, as in coronary artery disease (including acute coronary syndrome), signs and symptoms may include chest pain.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] The lesions of arteriosclerosis begin when the intima (the innermost layer of a blood vessel wall) of an artery starts to fill up with the deposition of cellular wastes.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] As these develop, they can take different forms of arteriosclerosis.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] All are linked through common features such as the stiffening of arterial vessels, thickening of arterial walls and the degenerative nature of the disease.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] Diagnosis of an individual suspected of having arteriosclerosis can be based on a physical exam, blood test, EKG and the results of these tests (among other exams).
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] Treatment is often in the form of preventive measures or prophylaxis.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] Lifestyle changes are also advised, such as increasing exercise, stopping smoking, and moderating alcohol intake.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] In 2008, the US had an estimate of 16 million cases of atherosclerotic heart disease and 5.8 million strokes.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] Cardiovascular diseases that were caused by arteriosclerosis also caused almost 812,000 deaths in 2008, more than any other cause, including cancer.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] About 1.2 million Americans are predicted to have a heart attack each year.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] The diagnostics and clinical implications of this disease were not recognized until the 20th century.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] Many cases have been observed and recorded, and Jean Lobstein coined the term *arteriosclerosis* while he was analyzing the composition of calcified arterial lesions.
[src:eleanora-knopf/arteriosclerosis] The name "arteriosclerosis" is derived the Greek words ἀρτηρία (*artēría*, artery) and σκληρωτικός (*sklērōtikós*, hardened).
[src:eleanora-knopf/birth-name] A **birth name** is the name a person is given when they are born.
[src:eleanora-knopf/birth-name] The term may be applied to the surname, the given name, or the full name.
[src:eleanora-knopf/birth-name] Where births are officially registered, the full birth name entered onto a birth register or birth certificate may become the person's legal name by that fact alone.
[src:eleanora-knopf/birth-name] The terms **née** (feminine) and **né** (masculine; both pronounced /neɪ/ ⓘ; from French *né[e]* 'born') are used to indicate a pre-marital maiden name or a birth name that was later changed.
[src:eleanora-knopf/birth-name] The term *née* has feminine grammatical gender and is used to denote a woman's surname at birth; *né* is the equivalent term for men.
[src:eleanora-knopf/birth-name] In most English-speaking cultures, *née* is specifically used to indicate a woman's maiden name after her surname is changed due to marriage.
[src:eleanora-knopf/birth-name] The diacritic marks (the acute accent) are considered significant to its spelling, and ultimately its meaning, but they are sometimes omitted.
[src:eleanora-knopf/birth-name] According to Oxford University's *Dictionary of Modern English Usage*, the terms are typically placed after the current surname; for example, 'Ann Smith, *née* Jones' or 'Adam Smith, *né* Jones' would represent people with the birth surname 'Jones' and current surname 'Smith'.
[src:eleanora-knopf/birth-name] Because these terms were adopted into English from French, they do not have to be italicized, but often are.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] The **Boulder Batholith** is a relatively small batholith in southwestern Montana, United States, exposed at the surface as granite (more specifically quartz monzonite) and serving as the host rock for rich mineralized deposits at Butte and other locations.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] The batholith lies roughly between Butte and Helena, and between the Deer Lodge (Upper Clark Fork) Valley and the Broadwater (Upper Missouri) Valley.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] The volcanic Elkhorn Mountains are a large mass of forested lava associated with the batholith.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] The batholith is composed of at least seven, and possibly as many as 14, discrete rock masses called plutons, which had formed beneath the Earth's surface during a period of magma intrusion about 73 to 78 million years ago (Late Cretaceous time).
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] The rising buoyant plutons resulted from subduction along what was then the west coast of North America, which was near today's border between Montana and Idaho.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] Regional uplift brought the deep-seated granite to the surface, where erosion exposed the rocks and the extremely rich mineral veins they contained.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] Hundreds of millions of dollars of copper, silver, gold, zinc, lead, and other metals have been mined from the batholith, both using underground mining and pit mining.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] The Butte Granite makes up the bulk of the batholith (about 70%), with additional named intrusions along the periphery consisting of granodiorite, monzogranite, and minor syenogranite.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] The batholith intruded into Mesoproterozoic and Mesozoic sedimentary rocks, including the Elkhorn Mountains volcanics.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] The origin of these igneous rocks is related to subduction and continental magmatic arc processes associated with the Late Cretaceous western margin of North America.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] Later hydrothermal vein activity along fault and shear zones within the Butte quartz monzonite and its contact with adjacent rocks, resulted in major ore deposits of lead, zinc, and silver.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] The Boulder Batholith was named for the prominent rounded boulders that typify its landscape, the result of spheroidal weathering of fractured granite.
[src:eleanora-knopf/boulder-batholith] It measures approximately 75 miles (121 km) north-south by about 25 miles (40 km) east-west, rather small in comparison to most batholiths.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Eleanora Frances Bliss was born in Rosemont, Pennsylvania on July 15, 1883.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Her father was General Tasker Howard Bliss — a career soldier who became Chief of Staff of the US Army during the First World War as well as a principal representative of the United States in the Allied Councils.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Her mother was Eleanora Emma (Anderson) Bliss.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Both sides of the family could trace their ancestry to settlers from England.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] The Bliss family home was located near crystalline rocks which she later studied.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She married geologist Adolph Knopf, in 1920.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] They did not have children of their own, but she became a stepmother to his three children, who were already of school age at the time.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She received her early education from Florence Baldwin School.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She attended Bryn Mawr College, where she earned her bachelor's degree in 1904.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She was a student of a remarkable woman and geologist Florence Bascom who was praised for her pioneering findings in Geology and had a major influence in the next generation of female geologists, including Eleanora Knopf, who studied the field.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] While Knopf was not recognized by Yale University for her accomplishments, she still extended her knowledge to others who specialized in Geology, especially the study of metamorphic rocks, and had started the Geology department at Florence Baldwin School.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Knopf completed both her undergraduate and graduate studies under Bascom.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Eleanora worked as a demonstrator in the geology lab at Bryn Mawr as well as an assistant curator in the Geological Museum at the college (1904 -1909).
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] After two years at Berkeley (1910-1911), she returned to Bryn Mawr to work with Anna Jonas Stose (another one of Bascom's students), on the study of the metamorphic rocks near the college.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Stose and Bliss had followed Bascom into the study of petrology.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] They presented their dissertation together and received doctorates in 1912.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] They collaborated on multiple papers, and went on to publish the most notable ones, such as one relating to the structure of metamorphic rocks called Schists, and another regarding the geology of McCalls Ferry.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She later went on to pursue a postdoctoral fellowship in geology at Johns Hopkins University (1917-1918).
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Eleanora was among 28 women who were elected for a fellowship, she was elected in 1919.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Shortly after receiving a Ph.D. in geology from Bryn Mawr and passing the civil service examinations, she went to Washington, DC to assist as a geological aide to the United States Geological Survey (USGS) in 1912 and continued her work on the metamorphic rocks on sites around Bryn Mawr.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] In 1913 she published her findings in the American Museum of Natural History of the first American sighting of mineral glaucophane, located in Pennsylvania which had never been found before in the east part of the Pacific Coast in the U.S.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] In 1917, she was promoted to a geological assistant where she worked with the Maryland State Geological Survey and the federal survey.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Later in 1920, she became an official Geologist.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] During this time, she was never given the opportunity to teach any material in a high-level academic setting.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She would still offer to teach geology students who reached out to her directly through informal teaching sessions, where she would teach them basic geologic concepts to direct field work practices.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] In the 1930s, she would go on to work as a visiting lecturer at both Yale and Harvard.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She continued to work for the USGS until 1955 on a *when actually employed* basis.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] In 1925 she began studying the rocks of the Stissing Mountain region.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] This study necessitated her attentiveness for the rest of her career.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] These presented unusual difficulty for examination purposes due to thrust faults.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] After searching overseas for new ways to precisely study the region, she settled upon the methods of Bruno Sander (from Innsbruck University) in which the fine structure of the rock was examined — the grains and the optical properties.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She translated his work and used it for the following 40 years in the United States for her studies, mastering this new technique.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] This technique of petrography was new to US geology.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Her book from 1938 on the subject, *Structural Petrography*, brought her much distinction.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Eleanora Knopf was one of several American women geologists who spent time working in the Appalachians during the twentieth century.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Though she was primarily a petrologist, she made astute observations concerning inequalities in erosion in catchments and hence the survival of palaeoforms in the landscape.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] Although these observations were opposed to one of primary principles of geomorphology at the time, Knopf implied that remnant landforms should still survive for an extended period due to unequal erosion.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] As a result of her research, her findings in elation to deformation and the visual effects of the rock formations lead to the creation a new division of Geological study.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] In 1951, she joined Stanford University in geology department as a research associate.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She continued to study the Stissing Mountain rocks until her retirement in 1955 but also made some expeditions to the Rocky Mountains.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] After retiring Eleanora Knopf moved out to the Rocky Mountains with her husband (Adolph Knopf) to aid him with his studies, after his death in 1966 she devoted herself to completing his research regarding the Boulder Batholith but health complications arose for her.
[src:eleanora-knopf/eleanora-knopf] She died in 1974 from arteriosclerosis in Menlo Park, California, at the age of 90.
